general 2018-12-14 16:59:05 (this is going to sound racist, but trust me, it's just studies and stuff) you know how a lot of black people have a gang talk? Well linguistic researchers whatever they're called actually say it's another dialect. It was made when Africans who only knew native languages came to America, and learned English but still kept a lot of their native language. They taught this to their kids, and the way they spoke had different meanings. Like "He be working" is actually correct in their dialect. It means "he is employed" or "he has a job/occupation", instead of what most people think it means; "he is working".

plane-crazy 2019-05-07 17:48:40 So I found out why my neural networks didn't work. Apparently when randomly generating the net I did ```lua
math.random(-10,10)/10```
But I looked at a professionally neural network library and it did
```lua
math random()*2-1```
Which is somehow different... But it worked so even though that means I basically wasted days and days doing debugging, I'm happy.

bug-reports 2020-03-26 01:09:25 If you have too many wings, or move too quickly with wings, they spaz out and glitch your plane to the far lands and out of existance.
Speculation: The wing panel lift equation might cause a positive feedback loop, where if there are enough wings, or going fast enough, it causes the wing to spaz, which would be seen as a lot of momentum, causing the wings to lift in the opposite direction, this time with more force due to the massive momentum, and so on and so forth.
If this is the case, then you could fix this by making the lift function not go above a certain limit, easiest way to do this is with a non linear function. My suggestion: Sigmoid[1/(1+2[the higher this is, the faster it will change while approaching 0]^-x)]

general 2020-09-10 04:42:37 i rewrote my neural network module to use matrix mathematics, and this time it takes up half the lines it did when i last wrote a neural network module
general 2020-09-10 04:42:40 check it out
general 2020-09-10 04:42:43 ```lua
local module = {}

local matmath = require(script.MatrixMathematics)

local max=math.max
local exp=math.exp
local function Activator(x) --leaky relu
    return max(0.1*x,x)
end

local function Sigmoid(x) --activator function for the final layer to add non-linearity
    return 1/(1+exp(-x))
end

function module.Create(Size) --creates a neural network
    local network={}
    local biases={}
    for i=1,#Size-1 do
        local nextnum=i+1
        network[i]=matmath.CreateRandom({Size[i],Size[nextnum]}, -2, 2)
        biases[i]=matmath.CreateRandom({1,Size[nextnum]}, -2, 2)
    end
    return {network, biases}
end

function module.Run(Network, Inputs) --input size: x by 1
    local compinp={}
    for i=1,#Inputs do
        compinp[i]={Inputs[i]}
    end
    
    local activations={}
    activations[1]=compinp
    for i=1,#Network[1]-1 do -- -1 because the output layer is done slightly differently
        local nextnum=i+1
        activations[nextnum]=matmath.Multiply(Network[1][i],activations[i])
        activations[nextnum]=matmath.Add(activations[nextnum],Network[2][i])
        activations[nextnum]=matmath.Map(activations[nextnum],Activator)
    end
    activations[#Network[1]+1]=matmath.Multiply(Network[1][#Network[1]],activations[#Network[1]])
    activations[#Network[1]+1]=matmath.Add(activations[#Network[1]+1],Network[2][#Network[1]])
    activations[#Network[1]+1]=matmath.Map(activations[#Network[1]+1],Sigmoid)
    
    return activations[#Network[1]]
end

return module```

general 2021-02-27 20:03:24 the idea behind my neural network learny thing is that each neuron connects to whatever other neurons are correct more often
general 2021-02-27 20:04:26 so ideally, if you connect to neurons that are correct more often, you will be correct more often than any of the neurons you're connected to, so whichever neurons think you're more correct will connect more strongly to you
general 2021-02-27 20:04:44 BRAINS
general 2021-02-27 20:04:57 ooh brb dog machine wants to come in
general 2021-02-27 20:06:23 back
general 2021-02-27 20:08:43 i give the neural network a score for how good it did in a specific run, and then when a neuron decides which neurons it wants to connect to, it thinks "aight, if i care about this neurons opinion(i do, since im activated), then if they are on, that means that in this specific context it is right and i want to be more right just like that neuron, so i will increase my connection to it so that whenever that neuron is on, i will be more likely to be on as well"
general 2021-02-27 20:08:56 theres a lot more very complicated thingies that go into it
general 2021-02-27 20:09:16 probably most complicated thing is the bias determining the threshold at which that neuron will let itself be activated
general 2021-02-27 20:09:31 yes
general 2021-02-27 20:09:36 thats what the bias does
general 2021-02-27 20:09:57 it wiggles around so that neurons are more likely to explore and find new patterns to connect in series of
general 2021-02-27 20:10:22 nope, no randomness at all
general 2021-02-27 20:10:51 basically the very simple explanation of how the bias moves is it moves in the opposite direction of the average activation of that neuron
general 2021-02-27 20:11:05 so if that neuron is off more often than it is on, it will try to push that neuron to be on more often
general 2021-02-27 20:11:08 and vice versa
general 2021-02-27 20:11:39 because that would make the neuron explore less and always be activated(or never be activated)
general 2021-02-27 20:11:56 which would cause that neuron to be a worthless piece of trash and useless to the network
general 2021-02-27 20:12:07 yeah
general 2021-02-27 20:12:17 think of it like mathematical communism
general 2021-02-27 20:12:22 everybody works together to make it work
general 2021-02-27 20:12:32 and if everybody works together, it is a very good system

general 2021-03-03 23:08:15 the learning function is super duper complicated and spaghetti-y, but the parameter tuner is super simple actually, ill show you in a sec
general 2021-03-03 23:08:39 the function made 7% progress in the last day, so its actually going really really fast
general 2021-03-03 23:14:00 heres what it looks like basically:
```lua
local currentParameters={1,1,1,1,1,1} --the parameters that need to be tuned
local parameterCounter=0
local bestParameters={nil,-1000} --initialize the best parameters
repeat
  local score=Test(currentParameters) --tests the current parameters to see how well they do
  if score>bestParameters[2] then
    bestParameters={currentParameters,score}
  end
  parameterCounter=parameterCounter+1
  currentParameters=bestParameters[1]
  currentParameters[parameterCounter]=currentParameters[parameterCounter]+random(-1,1)
  if parameterCounter>=#currentParameters then
    parameterCounter=0
  end
until nil```

general 2021-03-04 01:27:37 so that neuron has to rely on weight connections to change in order to find new answers

general 2021-03-04 01:28:09 uhhHH
general 2021-03-04 01:28:15 hmm let me figure out how i would do that
general 2021-03-04 01:28:57 well a neuron is just like a circle that does weird stuff with numbers
general 2021-03-04 01:29:37 the numbers that it does weird stuff with depend on connections between itself and another neuron, and what that connection describes
general 2021-03-04 01:30:24 so if the neuron and the neuron that its connected to agree a lot, the connection will be positive, meaning this neuron will be more likely to be turned on if the neuron its connected to is on
general 2021-03-04 01:31:05 if this neuron and the neuron it is connected to disagree a lot, the connection will be negative, so this neuron will be less like to be activated if the neuron its connected to is activated
general 2021-03-04 01:31:40 the bias is super duper complicated but the best way i can describe it is:
general 2021-03-04 01:31:52 well a neuron is a function, like f(x)
general 2021-03-04 01:32:08 and f(x)=mx+b, "b" is the BIAS
general 2021-03-04 01:33:01 a bias is basically a guaranteed number given to the neuron, so if the bias is more positive, this neuron will be more likely to activate more often
general 2021-03-04 01:33:11 if it is negative, this neuron is less likely to activate
general 2021-03-04 01:34:06 and what a learning function does is it decides how the weights(the connections to other neurons) and the biases should change in order to achieve a higher score or something like that
general 2021-03-04 01:34:48 the most common learning function is backpropagation, but i couldnt get it to work so im inventing my own learning function
general 2021-03-04 01:35:04 with backpropagation you have to tell the neural network the answer you want out of it
general 2021-03-04 01:35:11 with MY function you just have to tell it how good it did
general 2021-03-04 01:35:36 no, nononono not at all
general 2021-03-04 01:35:41 yeah
general 2021-03-04 01:35:56 if you tell it the score, its like calling a dog a good boy
general 2021-03-04 01:36:14 if you tell it the answer, its like doing a backflip to show your dog that you want it to do a backflip
general 2021-03-04 01:36:57 its a lot easier to tell something that it did good than it is to show it exactly what you want it to do
general 2021-03-04 01:37:03 and a lot more versatile

general 2021-03-04 01:41:02 but basically every time the network is run, the neuron looks at the other neurons it is connected to, and if the score is good, it connects more positively to neurons that are activated as well, and connects more negatively to neurons it disagrees with
general 2021-03-04 01:41:23 pretty simple for the weight adjustments
